#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NOTES / THINGS TO CHECK BEFORE YOU TRUST THIS OUTPUT
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. add_p()'s automatic categorical test: gtsummary defaults to chi-square and
#    automatically substitutes Fisher's exact when any expected cell count is
#    small -- this matches the intent of your safe_chisq_or_fisher(), but it is
#    gtsummary's own internal rule, not the identical expected<5 rule you wrote.
#    If you need the EXACT same rule, pass an explicit `test =` list per
#    variable instead of the two blanket defaults above.
# 2. add_p() for continuous variables above uses "t.test" for every continuous
#    row (to match the reference table's "Welch Two Sample t-test" footnote).
#    If MELD or cold ischemic time are skewed and you want Wilcoxon instead
#    (as your original calc_pvalues() did), set that variable's test
#    individually, e.g.:
#      add_p(test = list(MELD_PELD_LAB_SCORE ~ "wilcox.test", ...))
# 3. The reference table's footnote lists ONLY the tests that were actually
#    used. gtsummary always prints the same footnote text you supply in
#    modify_footnote(), so if you end up with a Wilcoxon test anywhere, update
#    that footnote string to say so (as the reference table does when it lists
#    both a t-test and a chi-square test together).
# 4. HLA_MM, ORGAN_LBL, RACE_LBL, PREV_ANY_LBL are multi-level categorical
#    variables -> gtsummary automatically prints ONE p-value on the variable's
#    header row, matching the "Race/ethnicity ... <0.001" merged-row look in
#    your reference tables, with no separate p-values on each level.
# 5. To export any of these as Word/PDF-ready tables, pipe into
#    as_flex_table() (Word) or as_gt() (further gt customization) or
#    as_kable_extra() (PDF via LaTeX) -- gtsummary supports all three.


